consts.name: PHP_ROUND_HALF_UP
consts.desc: Round val up to precision decimal places away from zero, when it is half way there. Making 1.5 into 2 and -1.5 into -2.

consts.name: PHP_ROUND_HALF_DOWN
consts.desc: Round val down to precision decimal places towards zero, when it is half way there. Making 1.5 into 1 and -1.5 into -1.

consts.name: PHP_ROUND_HALF_EVEN
consts.desc: Round val to precision decimal places towards the next even value.

consts.name: PHP_ROUND_HALF_ODD
consts.desc: Round val to precision decimal places towards the next odd value.

return.desc: The value of pi as float.

funcs.name: min
funcs.desc:
If the first and only parameter is an array, min() returns the lowest value in that array. If at least two parameters are provided, min() returns the smallest of these values.

PHP will evaluate a non-numeric string as 0 if compared to integer, but still return the string if it's seen as the numerically lowest value. If multiple arguments evaluate to 0, min() will return the lowest alphanumerical string value if any strings are given, else a numeric 0 is returned.

return.desc: min() returns the numerically lowest of the parameter values.

funcs.name: max
funcs.desc:
If the first and only parameter is an array, max() returns the highest value in that array. If at least two parameters are provided, max() returns the biggest of these values.

PHP will evaluate a non-numeric string as 0 if compared to integer, but still return the string if it's seen as the numerically highest value. If multiple arguments evaluate to 0, max() will return a numeric 0 if given, else the alphabetical highest string value will be returned.

return.desc:
max() returns the numerically highest of the parameter values. If multiple values can be considered of the same size, the one that is listed first will be returned.

When max() is given multiple arrays, the longest array is returned. If all the arrays have the same length, max() will use lexicographic ordering to find the return value.

When given a string it will be cast as an integer when comparing.

funcs.name: abs
funcs.desc: Returns the absolute value of number.

return.desc: The absolute value of number. If the argument number is of type float, the return type is also float, otherwise it is integer (as float usually has a bigger value range than integer).

funcs.name: is_finite
funcs.desc: Checks whether val is a legal finite on this platform.

return.desc: TRUE if val is a legal finite number within the allowed range for a PHP float on this platform, else FALSE.

funcs.name: is_infinite
funcs.desc: Returns TRUE if val is infinite (positive or negative), like the result of log(0) or any value too big to fit into a float on this platform.

return.desc: TRUE if val is infinite, else FALSE.

funcs.name: is_nan
funcs.desc: Checks whether val is 'not a number', like the result of acos(1.01).

return.desc: Returns TRUE if val is 'not a number', else FALSE.
value rounded up to the next highest integer. The return value of ceil() is still of type float as the value range of float is usually bigger than that of integer.
value rounded to the next lowest integer. The return value of floor() is still of type float because the value range of float is usually bigger than that of integer.

funcs.name: round
funcs.desc:
Returns the rounded value of val to specified precision (number of digits after the decimal point). precision can also be negative or zero (default).

PHP doesn't handle strings like "12,300.2" correctly by default. See converting from strings.

return.desc: The rounded value

args.name: precision
args.desc: The optional number of decimal digits to round to.

args.name: mode
args.desc: One of the PHP_ROUND_HALF_* constants to determine how rounding should occur.

funcs.name: deg2rad
funcs.desc: This function converts number from degrees to the radian equivalent.

return.desc: The radian equivalent of number

funcs.name: rad2deg
funcs.desc: This function converts number from radian to degrees.

return.desc: The equivalent of number in degrees

funcs.name: decbin
funcs.desc: Returns a string containing a binary representation of the given number argument.

return.desc: Binary string representation of number

funcs.name: dechex
funcs.desc: Returns a string containing a hexadecimal representation of the given number argument. The largest number that can be converted is 4294967295 in decimal resulting to "ffffffff".

return.desc: Hexadecimal string representation of number

funcs.name: decoct
funcs.desc: Returns a string containing an octal representation of the given number argument. The largest number that can be converted is 4294967295 in decimal resulting to "37777777777".

return.desc: Octal string representation of number

funcs.name: bindec
funcs.desc:
Returns the decimal equivalent of the binary number represented by the binary_string argument.

bindec() converts a binary number to an integer or, if needed for size reasons, float.

bindec() interprets all binary_string values as unsigned integers. This is because bindec() sees the most significant bit as another order of magnitude rather than as the sign bit.
Warning

The parameter must be a string. Using other data types will produce unexpected results.

return.desc: The decimal value of binary_string

funcs.name: hexdec
funcs.desc:
Returns the decimal equivalent of the hexadecimal number represented by the hex_string argument. hexdec() converts a hexadecimal string to a decimal number.

hexdec() will ignore any non-hexadecimal characters it encounters.

return.desc: The decimal representation of hex_string

funcs.name: octdec
funcs.desc: Returns the decimal equivalent of the octal number represented by the octal_string argument.

return.desc: The decimal representation of octal_string

funcs.name: base_convert
funcs.desc: Returns a string containing number represented in base tobase. The base in which number is given is specified in frombase. Both frombase and tobase have to be between 2 and 36, inclusive. Digits in numbers with a base higher than 10 will be represented with the letters a-z, with a meaning 10, b meaning 11 and z meaning 35. Warning base_convert() may lose precision on large numbers due to properties related to the internal "double" or "float" type used. Please see the Floating point numbers section in the manual for more specific information and limitations.

return.desc: number converted to base tobase

args.name: tobase
args.desc: The base to convert number to

funcs.name: pow
funcs.desc:
Returns base raised to the power of exp. Warning

In PHP 4.0.6 and earlier pow() always returned a float, and did not issue warnings.

return.desc: base raised to the power of exp. If the result can be represented as integer it will be returned as type integer, else it will be returned as type float. If the power cannot be computed FALSE will be returned instead.

funcs.name: exp
funcs.desc:
Returns e raised to the power of arg.

'e' is the base of the natural system of logarithms, or approximately 2.718282.

return.desc: 'e' raised to the power of arg

funcs.name: expm1
funcs.desc: expm1() returns the equivalent to 'exp(arg) - 1' computed in a way that is accurate even if the value of arg is near zero, a case where 'exp (arg) - 1' would be inaccurate due to subtraction of two numbers that are nearly equal.

return.desc: 'e' to the power of arg minus one

funcs.name: log10
funcs.desc: Returns the base-10 logarithm of arg.

return.desc: The base-10 logarithm of arg

funcs.name: log1p
funcs.desc: log1p() returns log(1 + number) computed in a way that is accurate even when the value of number is close to zero. log() might only return log(1) in this case due to lack of precision.

return.desc: log(1 + number)

funcs.name: log
funcs.desc: If the optional base parameter is specified, log() returns logbase arg, otherwise log() returns the natural logarithm of arg.

return.desc: The logarithm of arg to base, if given, or the natural logarithm.

args.name: arg
args.desc: The value to calculate the logarithm for

args.name: base
args.desc: The optional logarithmic base to use (defaults to 'e' and so to the natural logarithm).

funcs.name: cos
funcs.desc: cos() returns the cosine of the arg parameter. The arg parameter is in radians.

return.desc: The cosine of arg

funcs.name: cosh
funcs.desc: Returns the hyperbolic cosine of arg, defined as (exp(arg) + exp(-arg))/2.

return.desc: The hyperbolic cosine of arg

funcs.name: sin
funcs.desc: sin() returns the sine of the arg parameter. The arg parameter is in radians.

return.desc: The sine of arg

funcs.name: sinh
funcs.desc: Returns the hyperbolic sine of arg, defined as (exp(arg) - exp(-arg))/2.

return.desc: The hyperbolic sine of arg

funcs.name: tan
funcs.desc: tan() returns the tangent of the arg parameter. The arg parameter is in radians.

return.desc: The tangent of arg

args.name: arg
args.desc: The argument to process in radians

funcs.name: tanh
funcs.desc: Returns the hyperbolic tangent of arg, defined as sinh(arg)/cosh(arg).

return.desc: The hyperbolic tangent of arg

funcs.name: acos
funcs.desc: Returns the arc cosine of arg in radians. acos() is the complementary function of cos(), which means that a==cos(acos(a)) for every value of a that is within acos()' range.

return.desc: The arc cosine of arg in radians.

funcs.name: acosh
funcs.desc: Returns the inverse hyperbolic cosine of arg, i.e. the value whose hyperbolic cosine is arg.

return.desc: The inverse hyperbolic cosine of arg

funcs.name: asin
funcs.desc: Returns the arc sine of arg in radians. asin() is the complementary function of sin(), which means that a==sin(asin(a)) for every value of a that is within asin()'s range.

return.desc: The arc sine of arg in radians

funcs.name: asinh
funcs.desc: Returns the inverse hyperbolic sine of arg, i.e. the value whose hyperbolic sine is arg.

return.desc: The inverse hyperbolic sine of arg

funcs.name: atan
funcs.desc: Returns the arc tangent of arg in radians. atan() is the complementary function of tan(), which means that a==tan(atan(a)) for every value of a that is within atan()'s range.

return.desc: The arc tangent of arg in radians.

funcs.name: atanh
funcs.desc: Returns the inverse hyperbolic tangent of arg, i.e. the value whose hyperbolic tangent is arg.

return.desc: Inverse hyperbolic tangent of arg
The arc tangent of y/x in radians.

funcs.name: hypot
funcs.desc: hypot() returns the length of the hypotenuse of a right-angle triangle with sides of length x and y, or the distance of the point (x, y) from the origin. This is equivalent to sqrt(x*x + y*y).

return.desc: Calculated length of the hypotenuse

funcs.name: fmod
funcs.desc: Returns the floating point remainder of dividing the dividend (x) by the divisor (y). The reminder (r) is defined as: x = i * y + r, for some integer i. If y is non-zero, r has the same sign as x and a magnitude less than the magnitude of y.

return.desc: The floating point remainder of x/y

funcs.name: sqrt
funcs.desc: Returns the square root of arg.

return.desc: The square root of arg or the special value NAN for negative numbers.
The largest possible random value returned by rand()

funcs.name: srand
funcs.desc: Seeds the random number generator with seed or with a random value if no seed is given. As of PHP 4.2.0, there is no need to seed the random number generator with srand() or mt_srand() as this is now done automatically.

return.desc: No value is returned.
A pseudo random value between min (or 0) and max (or getrandmax(), inclusive).

args.name: max
args.desc: The highest value to return (default: getrandmax())

return.desc: Returns the maximum random value returned by mt_rand()

funcs.name: mt_srand
funcs.desc: Seeds the random number generator with seed or with a random value if no seed is given. As of PHP 4.2.0, there is no need to seed the random number generator with srand() or mt_srand() as this is now done automatically.

return.desc: No value is returned.
A random integer value between min (or 0) and max (or mt_getrandmax(), inclusive)

args.name: min
args.desc: Optional lowest value to be returned (default: 0)

args.name: max
args.desc: Optional highest value to be returned (default: mt_getrandmax())

funcs.name: lcg_value
funcs.desc: lcg_value() returns a pseudo random number in the range of (0, 1). The function combines two CGs with periods of 2^31 - 85 and 2^31 - 249. The period of this function is equal to the product of both primes.

return.desc: A pseudo random float value in the range of (0, 1)
